- "Radiate the most energy" refers to tracks with the highest average energy values;
- "Playlist presence" refers to the total number of tracks by an artist that appear in playlists;
- "Fan following" refers to the number of followers an artist has;
- "Overall popularity" refers to the popularity score of the artist.

- 'Brightness' refers to the artist's popularity;
- 'Played in different galaxies' refers to the number of unique playlists where the artist's tracks appear;
- 'Size of their constellation' refers to the number of artists in the same genre;
- 'Overall luminosity' is the calculated overall popularity score.

- The term "tracks" refers to individual songs or music pieces;
- The term "albums" refers to collections of tracks released as a single product;
- The artist with the most tracks is determined by the total number of tracks they have across all their albums.

- 'most admired' refers to the genres with the highest average artist popularity;
- 'unique artists' refers to the number of distinct artists associated with each genre;
- 'collectively offer' refers to the total number of tracks across all albums in each genre.

- "Shining stars in the music universe" refers to artists with high popularity and a significant number of followers;
- "Tunes that move the masses" refers to tracks with high danceability scores;
- "Made it into playlists" refers to tracks that are included in user playlists.

- "Top tracks" refers to tracks in the first three positions of the playlist;
- "Danceability" is a measure of how suitable a track is for dancing to, based on a combination of musical elements including tempo, rhythm stability, beat strength, and overall regularity;
- "Albums with more than 10 tracks" indicates that the artist has at least one album containing more than 10 tracks.

sql:
SELECT AVG(T1.popularity) AS average_stardom
FROM artists T1
WHERE T1.followers > (SELECT AVG(followers) FROM artists);

SELECT COUNT(artist_id) 
FROM artists 
WHERE popularity > (SELECT AVG(popularity) FROM artists);

